**Explanation:** The `debounce` function delays invoking a given function until a certain amount of time has passed since the last time it was invoked. This is useful for optimizing performance, for example, when handling user input in a search box.

**JavaScript code:**

```javascript
// Debounce function
function debounce(func, wait) {
  let timeout;
  return function executedFunc(...args) {
    clearTimeout(timeout);
    timeout = setTimeout(() => func.apply(this, args), wait);
  };
}

// Usage example:
const heavyFunction = () => {
  console.log('Heavy function called!');
};

const debouncedHeavyFunction = debounce(heavyFunction, 300); // Debounce heavyFunction with a delay of 300ms

// Simulate user input events:
setTimeout(() => debouncedHeavyFunction(), 100);
setTimeout(() => debouncedHeavyFunction(), 200);
setTimeout(() => debouncedHeavyFunction(), 350);
setTimeout(() => debouncedHeavyFunction(), 500);
```

In this example, the `debounce` function delays the execution of `heavyFunction` until 300ms after the last time it was invoked. Despite being called four times, `heavyFunction` will only be executed once after 350ms, when the debounced delay has passed.
